<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;font-size:medium;"><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline"><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">The Long Road Home</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
<br>
A tavern. How she loved a good tavern. The bustling people, the smell of alcohol, unwashed people, and excitement. Most her life had revolved around taverns one way or another, it was her earliest recollection and the place where she felt most at home. Anything could happen, and usually did.<br>
<br>
Aaldari deposited some coins on the bar and collected her drink from the bartender. Making her way through the crowd, she spotted her companion, a well-dressed paladin who looked very uncomfortable sitting in the middle of the room. He fidgeted and had not touched his drink even though he had been waiting for her for a short while.<br>
<br>
Aaldari beamed a smile at him and plopped herself down at the table, putting her feet up on the chair between them. “Kaldahar! So good to see ya again me old friend!” <br>
<br>
Kaldahar grinned. “Oh you knew I was coming. Don’t pretend. But I am afraid I do not bring news that you find favorable.”<br>
<br>
The smile quickly disappeared from Aaldari’s face. “The council won't vote on me?”<br>
<br>
Kaldahar sighed wearily. “The council will vote on you. As a matter of fact, they already have.” She immediately sat up, foot making a loud sound as they crashed to the floor. Her mouth hung open for a moment before she spoke.<br>
<br>
“They voted? Without me being there? But…..” Her voice trailed off as her thoughts were in a whirlwind of confusion. “but…how am I supposed to present meself if they voted already?” She then realized he had not said what the vote was. Her glare turned to him as he sat, inspecting his drink, which he still had not touched. “Kal, what did they vote?”<br>
<br>
Kaldahar spoke quietly, “I am very sorry Aal, but you will not be a member of the Paladin Council.” He said his words with such finality; she did not speak for a long time. She finally blurted, “ I don’t understand. Perspectives are supposed to be there to answer…..”<br>
<br>
“They felt there was no need. The facts were there. Based on those facts they voted. Nothing you could have said would have changed their minds.”<br>
<br>
Kaldahar shifted as he watched the torrent of emotions run through her face. She gulped down her drink and quickly returned with a new one.<br>
<br>
“YOU are in consideration for the council, Lenara is and she is a moron. Untiki has collaborated with Tier’ Dal and yet he sits on the damned council!”<br>
<br>
“Aaldari do not talk like that. I have worked hard for my consideration. You know the others reasons for those two being on the council.”<br>
<br>
“Oh ya. Family for Lenara. Untiki…well this is just…wrong. I think I will go there and say something. I can’t believe this.”<br>
<br>
“Aaldari, don’t. Let it be. Maybe in time. But more work needs to be done on your part to prove your loyalty and qualifications.”<br>
<br>
“My qualifications?” A small laugh escaped from her. “And I am sure ye didn’t damage yer own standing by speaking for me!”<br>
<br>
Instantly she knew she had gone too far. His face became enraged. “Yes as a matter of fact, I did. And my vote has been postponed. More than likely the spot will be filled before my vote comes up. We have been friends a long time, but I warned you before that this was not a good idea! But you would not heed my word!”<br>
<br>
Even though she knew she had already pushed him, her anger was also building. Deep down she knew they would not accept her but she never let herself admit it. “Just because I do not have the family connection or the money to BUY me way into the council it’s NOT FAIR!” Several patrons looked her way as her voice rose. “What EXACTLY were the reasons for saying no?”<br>
<br>
“Aal, you do not want to get into this. I am warning you.”<br>
<br>
“Aye, that I do.”<br>
<br>
“Fine. You will find out from one person or another. You were right about one thing. You do not have the family connections. As a matter of fact, you have no family period. Hell, you CHOSE a last name. You did not endear yourself to one of the known families and adopted their name out of respect.”<br>
<br>
“Just as I thought!”<br>
<br>
“Aal, it’s not like you come from prestigious upbringing. Others have not as well but have gone bout things differently. The accepted way. Not gone all about it alone like you have. The are ways to do things.”<br>
<br>
“That can’t be the only reason.”<br>
<br>
“No. It wasn’t. How do you expect to sit on the council when you have had no formal schooling of any kind?”<br>
<br>
Aaldari gasped. “So me skills aren’t acceptable?”<br>
<br>
“No, they are not. All you can barely read and write for Marr’s sake! How are you supposed to teach and do the parchment work involved? You are not literate. The clerics in the temples do not know you! And then the biggest reason probably….”<br>
<br>
“And pray tell what that be?”<br>
<br>
“You have a drinking problem.” He said simply.<br>
<br>
Aaldari immediately began to defend herself. Kaldahar put up his hand to silence her. “Any one of these is reason enough not to be admitted on the council. But these were the reasons given. But they can be corrected with time.”<br>
<br>
“I will NOT change me name!”<br>
<br>
“No one is asking you to. But this is what you have to work on if you want to be on the council in Felwithe. And I am sorry old friend but I am expected elsewhere and must go. I am sorry I had to bring you such news.”<br>
<br>
He stood up and waited a moment. When she sat looking at the floor, he finally turned and left the tavern.<br>
<br>
She sat nursing her drink and collecting her thoughts. The one thing she had wanted for a long time, recognition, respect, was now closed to her. Working on the points he had stated did not occur to her. She was who she was. She did not change so easily. But what to do now? The new guildhall should be finishing completion within a day or two. The little band she had gathered together was her family now. She had no other. Family is not in name only but in actions. <br>
<br>
The afternoon passed slowly as she sat, alone with her thoughts. Patrons came and went. A female sitting alone in a tavern always attracted attention. A few started to approach, saw her sword and thought better. Her family needed her now she came to the conclusion. Abandon her old dream and see a new future. A new future with a new family. She smiled a little to herself already lighter having shed even the desire to ever be seated on the council. Downing her last drink she got up and left Qeynos for the long road home to West Commons.<br>
<br>
The plains in summer are always lovely, even with the plague. The birds are signing; the grass is soft and fragrant. If you stop you can pick out the different flower’s fragrances. Many animals pass by. So many, one cannot walk two feet without seeing one. The plains teem with life and she was seeing them with new, open eyes. With no set goal, no immediate place to go, she was seeing things she normally overlooked. Strolling rather than walking briskly, she savored the sights before her.<br>
<br>
Darkness encroached on her eyesight. When her view became more and more limited, she realized how far yet she had to go to reach Highpass and a safe resting spot. The plains may be beautiful, but they still hold dangers. She picked up her pace and headed toward Highkeep. But even as she raced the setting sun, she knew she would probably be walking half the night. <br>
<br>
Night fell quickly. She was still far from the cliffs. Her sight was hindered by the darkness. She cursed herself for not keeping a lantern with her. The human eyes are not made for nighttime travel and she was being reminded of her carelessness now. Suddenly, she heard a crack behind her. Any one of a hundred nocturnal creatures could have made the sound, but this one made her freeze. She slowly drew her sword and look around, but could not see anyone or anything. She began walking slowly, cautiously. She felt something was near and was not of a friendly nature. Walking faster, her heart racing, she broke into a run. Suddenly a sharp, piercing pain erupted in her neck. She dropped her sword to grasp the dart that was now embedded there. The darkness overwhelmed her as she slumped the ground unconscious.<br>
