<br>
Pain pounded in her head as she fought the darkness.  Waves of pain washed over her and the darkness clouded her sight, weighing her down like a heavy blanket.  Slowly, the weight seemed to lift as she concentrated on calming her mind and healing herself.  The power of magic always took all of her concentration, a task she could never seem to grasp properly.  Warm waves of healing finally replaced the sharp cold contrast of pain to bring her back to Norrath.  <br>
<br>
Slowly, she opened her eyes to view what she inevitably knew would be new surroundings.  All she saw was inky blackness surrounding her.  A trembling hand reached up to touch the open eyelid, as if the touch could erase what she could not bring herself to admit.  Her eyes were indeed open, yet she could not see anything at all.  Just a void.  A hollow pit formed in her stomach.  All her aches and pains were now forgotten.  She did not notice the cold steel band around her ankle attached to a heavy chain.  The fact that her possessions had been stripped from her and then she only wore a shift and pants did not penetrate her thoughts.  She struggled with the fact the entire world was now shut out to her, suddenly, without recourse.<br>
<br>
A low chuckle brought her attention back to her surroundings.  Heard, but unseen, one of her captors entered the tent in which she lay.  She froze, instantly thinking on the defensive.  “Who are you and what is going on here?” she demanded, never one to approach things lightly or unwearyingly.<br>
<br>
The air before her seemed to thicken signifying he had stepped closer.  She resisted the urge to reach out and test the air in front of her.  He must be very close yet she had heard no movement or breathing.  Something about the person’s laugh chilled her to the very bone.  As if evil itself had a voice.<br>
<br>
“That is for others to tell you of your fate.”<br>
<br>
The words silenced her.  The voice was icy cold, and he spoke barley above a whisper, yet his voice was very clear and loud.  But had he actually spoken out loud? It seemed to her that he had not.  That she had heard his voice inside her head.  Aaldari was positive it was a male voice but had never heard such a voice before.  At last she threw aside her reservations and threw out her hand to reach for the voice in front of her.<br>
<br>
There was nothing but empty air to meet her hand.<br>
<br>
Wincing from the bruises, she sat up and felt the area around her, trying to decipher where she was and why.  She felt loose, cool dirt covering hard rock.  Her hand soon found the food left by the mysterious person.  The food eaten, she returned to her search.  The chain that bound her was too strong and nothing in her search reveled any way out.  There was no apparent end to the chain and she could not move much without rattling it which was sure to bring her captor’s attention.  There seemed to be no furniture near here except a rolled up hide which she assumed was meant for her to lie on.  <br>
<br>
Every so often she touched her face as if to remind herself that there really was no blindfold invading her vision.  She could not, in her own mind come to terms with that just yet, there was too much else to think about.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>I am in the mountains of the Karanas somewhere.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  She thought to herself.  I am sure of that.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>That is, unless I was unconscious for a very long time.  So if that is true then…..</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
A cold chill ran thru her, stilling her blood.  There could be only one reason why the bandits would want her, she thought.  She thought back to the days when she was going thru her paladin trials.  In order to be recognized in Qeynos, she had to prove her worth and honor.   How many bandits had she killed to prove to the priests in Qeynos her worth?  How many sashes had she presented them?  She could no longer remember it was so long ago.  Yet the memories of the battles remained fresh in her mind and the blood on her hands would never be washed away.  The blood spilled in the name of honor.<br>
