<br>
Aaldari grunted as the man’s foot met her ribs.  She slowly rose to her feet to face where she assumed he was standing.  She marveled at how even a simple thing such as standing without weaving was much harder when you cannot see.<br>
<br>
“Who are you and what be ye doing?”  A hand reached out of the darkness, knocking her back and down the ground again.  She cursed her own helplessness.<br>
<br>
“Methinks ye shall keep your mouth shut, wench.  We need you alive but not necessarily whole.”<br>
<br>
Her mind began to whirl with thoughts.   Obviously this was not revenge as she had thought.  Unless of course they merely needed her alive until they decided the proper torture.<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
“Aye, yer people won’t pay if ye be dead I am sure.  Well, maybe they will but not near as much I reckon.”  She blinked at his offhanded comment and laughed.  The men who had entered the tent murmured amongst themselves, not liking she was laughing rather than frightened.  <br>
<br>
She was to be ransomed! It all made sense now and the relief washed over her in a wave.    “And the blindness, I assume, be temporary?” She asked quietly so as not to arouse more anger.<br>
<br>
“Aye.  It be temporary.  Can be easily cured once we receive payment and make delivery.”  She shuddered slightly, realizing they meant delivery of her.&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp <br>
<br>
“I hope yer people have plenty money saved up.  Now who should we send a message to?”<br>
<br>
She sighed, hating to give any information to help them but the more information they had, the quicker this would go.  “Who?” the bandit demanded.<br>
<br>
“A fair elven paladin by the name of Ephexian.  Son of Laraellian.  He resides in West Commons and was there last I know.  He would be the one to contact.”<br>
<br>
“So be it.  Ye shall wait here until we get our money.  Ye better hope yer people come through for ye.”<br>
<br>
The men left the tent, however one remained behind.  She felt the cold emanating from him as he approached.  The man studied her as if sizing her up.   She felt his eyes crawl over her as if she stood there naked, even though she was fully clothed.  Yet strangely she felt calm, much calmer than she had since she woke.  Ever more so in fact than she had ever felt possibly her entire life.<br>
<br>
“So you lead that group who call themselves the Edgers?”<br>
<br>
She nodded, “Aye that I do.  But do not presume I will tell you anything other than you need, for I will not.”<br>
<br>
“Oh you will tell me anything I need or want to know, woman.” She shrank from his voice, the icy coldness of it.  Yet she also felt drawn to him.  His voice was unlike the other bandits.  It did not have the wilderness harshness to it.  Without the distraction of sight, all she could tell about the people around her were by their voices.  And she could tell his was different no matter how much he tried to hide it.  There was something hypnotizing about him.  About his voice.  His very presence.  Something within her mind departed and her mind stood open with no barriers.  She would tell him anything as if he had a right or privilege.  She could hold no secrets from him.  She had no will to.<br>
