<br>
Even though there is much disparage among the races as to the content and purpose of heaven and hell, most agree they exist.  Almost all the races in some form or another agree heaven is warm and fluffy but hell is fire and brimstone.  They are all very wrong.<br>
<br>
Hell is cold.  Vast expanses of ice and cold and total absence of color.  Nothing but whiteness making the chill even worse, deep inside, where no amount of warmth can ever each.  Hell is the pain of that coldness, the coldness that no fire, no blanket will erase.<br>
<br>
Aaldari firmly believed she was being led through hell herself that very moment.  Even though still blind, she could feel the vast emptiness around her.  The ground was pure ice underneath her feet, scoured clean by harsh winds and the snow packed so hard it was now solid.  She winced as the bitter wind drove bits of snow to cut her like sand during a sandstorm.  The wind and snow scoured her skin raw and quickly snatched away any heat her body tried to produce.  She was beyond being cold, beyond numbness; into a realm of feeling she could no longer express with words.  With no patience for the paladin who was unfit for travel, underclothed and no exercise the past few weeks, they pushed her to move as quickly as they could towards their destination known only to them.  The bandits had changed their plans and were now quickening their pace to a new destination, with a much bigger treasure in mind.<br>
<br>
She stumbled along the hard ground in her tattered shoes, threatening to fall apart at any second, best she could, all fight now gone from her.  Her supposed lover walked in front of her.  His walk was well known to her by now but all love was lost between them.  She now knew him for what he was.  The toying and games were finished; he no longer put up the front of the concerned lover who would help her escape.   She had felt it when he hit her, her head clearing, her sight becoming remarkably clear, as if she had just woke from a dream.  It was the only time he had touched her that she could remember with clarity, ungentle, but in that one touch, too much was communicated.  More than words can ever say.  Many days had passed, how many, she did not know.  They all seemed to flow one into the other.  She could have only marked the passage of time by the meals served, but after a few days with this unseen Bandit, she had not cared.  All she had cared about was him, his words, his touch.  After awhile, thought of escape no longer came to her.  She no longer cared about anything but him. The love she had once had for this man was completely gone in the realization his promises were so many empty words meant to induce her to submission with words she had so longed to hear from any man.   In that one touch she had not recoiled from the pain but from the pure evil and hatred she had felt emanating from his hand.  It disgusted her and she recoiled from it.  In one instant she realized what a fool she had been.  She had betrayed herself with her own weakness.  She vowed if she lived through this ordeal she would never let herself fail to her own weakness again.  <br>
<br>
He shoved her forward, harshly, trying to get her to hurry.  The small band trudged on wearily, for they could not take the main roads, but stayed hidden in the short hillsides.  Aaldari struggled to keep up, her worry growing with each painful step.  She was not clothed for this weather and they had not provided much.  She imagined her feet made of wood, as were her hands, that is until they touched the ice when she stumbled.  Then they burned with a pain she couldn’t have imagined before.  They were not taking her to her guild for ransom anymore.  She did not know exactly when the plans were changed, but this was clearly not the way to any meeting place her guild would have agreed to.    So where were they going? Did someone offer a higher ransom? She had no idea how these things worked but surely they did not just put up a for-sale sign in the local towns.<br>
<br>
The trek took days and the bandits wondered if their package would last the trip.  She walked slower and slower and her feet were bleeding.  She didn’t seem to realize it though and they did not tell her nor treat her injuries.  They grumbled to each other over their troubles, yet the one she knew the best was clearly calmer than the others.  He cared little about ransoms and money.  <br>
<br>
Finally, after what seemed like an eternity, her feet struck stone.  But not any stone.  She knew instantly where they had taken her and she froze in place refusing to move.  Her feet, even though frozen, remembered quite clearly the stone which they had tread upon for many a long day and it was the only place that made sense.<br>
<br>
“No.  Just kill me here.  Now.” She said with conviction, knowing what fate lay ahead of her anyway.<br>
<br>
“And deprive the Lady of her pleasure and us of our money? Not a chance.  Move!”<br>
<br>
They shoved her forward into the lair.  She had neither the strength nor ability to resist.  Deeper into the lair they wandered, soon met by the guards of the lair who guided them deeper into the depths of the caverns.  The cavern walls glittered brightly from unseen light source.  Some passages were tricky to negotiate.  The ice in some parts was so clear it formed an invisible wall.  There were many unseen pit traps and creatures along the way who watched them pass with their escort but left them unmolested.  <br>
<br>
Eventually, Aaldari realized they walked into an open chamber.  The air around her was much larger and the group was not so tightly packed.  The bandits conversed with the unknown creatures that guided them in a language she did not understand and then she heard their footsteps turn to leave and soon there was silence.  Not even a whisper.  She began to shiver and not just from the cold.<br>
