<br>
“There is no longer need for the binders.  Be cured and look upon me.”<br>
<br>
Aaldari felt warmth fringed with coldness emanate from her eyes.  Within a few seconds her sight started to return.  She kept her head lowered; while she struggled with the light she had wanted back for so long which was now a painful torture to her so long in the dark eyes.  The rope tying her hands together split, seemingly of its own accord and fell to the ground, freeing her completely.<br>
<br>
“Can you not look upon me, paladin?”<br>
<br>
She could not raise her head.  She knew exactly who that voice came from.  The booming intonation, yet barely above a whisper.  The creature who had come here to make a home and carved the vast caverns herself.  The one who lorded over the many creatures that dwelled in the caves but also many more powerful creatures in many distant lands.<br>
<br>
“Greetings milady Vox.”<br>
<br>
“So you do know me.”<br>
<br>
“Aye.”<br>
<br>
The ground shook as the giant dragon slowly walked towards her.  Aaldari forced herself to look up as the Lady approached, not willing to die with her eyes on the ground.  She unfurled her wings and stretched them out behind.  She was a spectacular sight indeed.  Her coat gleamed pure white.  A white unlike anything that could ever be seen by mortal eyes.  She was of the noble dragons, renowned for her powers and intelligence even amongst her own kind.  Her long neck stretched out till her head was very near Aaldari.<br>
<br>
Aaldari was startled to have a dragon so close to her and still be alive.  Goblin guards stood by but well out of the way.  Lady Vox’s was so close but yet made sure not to breathe directly on the paladin.  Yet she still felt her breath.  She could not even describe it in words to herself.  It seemed to freeze her very soul.<br>
<br>
“What gave you the right to kill my guards?  To kill my captain?  You entered my home, uninvited, unwarranted and stole from me.”<br>
<br>
“I be not a thief…….” Before she could finish her sentence she was knocked backwards flat on her back with Vox’s paw pressing precariously down on her.  She felt a trickle of blood run down her leg from a slash across her thigh.  Slowly the pain came through the numbness in her body.  Vox could easily have killed her but had just reminded her of the fact by slicing her leg.  Lady Vox was a cleric and was known for healing her victims so she could prolong their torture when they displeased her.<br>
<br>
“But you are, mortal.  You stole not only bounty from here but lives as well.  If it was possible to teach one of your kind anything, I would keep you here.  But since it is not, I have not yet decided to kill you myself or give you to my goblins to play with.  They do not have short memories.”<br>
<br>
Her thigh was beginning to sting.  Yet another pain to add to her many others, but it was somehow distracting her.  “Milady.  I have no excuses except that I was young when I was here last and I was wrong.  I came to prove my valor to Paladin guild for the trials.  I know now I was wrong, but I do not know how to make amends.  I am sorry.”<br>
<br>
“Interesting.  But more than likely you are telling me what I want to hear to save your own sorry skin.”  Suddenly she lifted her paw up off Aaldari.  Aaldari cringed afraid it would come down much harder this time.  She made no attempt to get to her feet.  But the dragon was not even looking at her.  She was looking intently at the underside of her own paw.  Suddenly, without warning and swifter than Aaldari could even breathe, Vox swiped her paw across Aaldari’s legs.  So precise was her pass she sliced open the pants on her injured leg without harming the skin or muscles any farther.<br>
<br>
“The mark!” the dragon cried.<br>
